e":"1161–Overleden","1183–1215":"1183–1215","1120–1161":"1120–1161","about 1161":"circa 1161","1215":"1215","between 1164-1174":"van 1164 to 1174","1263":"1263","1120":"1120","before 1161":"vóór 1161","1140":"1140","before 1140":"vóór 1140","1183":"1183","1161":"1161","Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Schotland","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Europe":"Europa","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Schotland","North Ayshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Schotland"},"en":{"1140–":"1140–Deceased","1140–Male":"1140–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1161–Male":"1161–Deceased","1183–1215":"1183–1215","1120–1161":"1120–1161","about 1161":"about 1161","1215":"1215","between 1164-1174":"from 1164 to 1174","1263":"1263","1120":"1120","before 1161":"before 1161","1140":"1140","before 1140":"before 1140","1183":"1183","1161":"1161","Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland","North Ayshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Somerville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: of Norman origin, a habitational name from Graveron-Sémerville in Eure (Normandy), from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sigimar</i> (see   Siemer  ) + Old French <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. The surname was taken to Scotland in the 12th century by William <i>de Somerville</i>, a retainer of David, Earl of Huntingdon, who became King David I of Scotland.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Somacháin</b> (see   Summers  ) or <b>Mag Shamradháin</b> (see   Somers  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Siemer","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Helmut, Helmuth, Otto, Theresia.","German: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Siegmar</i>, composed of the elements <i>sigi</i> ‘victory’ + <i>mari</i>, <i>meri</i> ‘famous’."]},{"name":"Sommerville","meanings":["Scottish (Lanarkshire): variant of   Somerville   1."]},{"name":"Summerville","meanings":["English, Scottish (Lanarkshire), and Irish: variant of   Somerville  . This form of the surname is particularly common in Ireland."]},{"name":"Simrell","meanings":["Scottish: perhaps related to the Ulster name<b>Sumeril</b>, a variant of   Somerville  ."]},{"name":"Summerfield","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called with Old English <i>sumor</i> ‘summer’ + <i>feld</i> ‘field, open land’, denoting summer pasture or fields cultivated only in summer, such as Summerfield in Woodnesborough (Kent), Somerfield Court in Sellindge (Kent), and Summerfield in Marlborough (Wiltshire).","English: variant of   Somerville  .","Americanized form (translation into English) of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Sommerfeld  , a cognate of 1 above."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William de Somerville was born in 1140, in Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of William de Somerville and wife William de Somerville. He married wife William de Somerville of Lanarkshire before 1161, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He registered for military service in 1263. He died in his hometown."},"et":{"1140–":"1140–Surnud","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1161–Male":"1161–Surnud","1183–1215":"1183–1215","1120–1161":"1120–1161","about 1161":"umbes 1161","1215":"1215","between 1164-1174":"1164 kuni 1174","1263":"1263","1120":"1120","before 1161":"enne 1161","1140":"1140","before 1140":"enne 1140","1183":"1183","1161":"1161","Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Europe":"Europe","Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Carnwath, Lanarkshire, Scotland","North Ayshire, Scotland":"Ayrshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1140–":"1140–Kuollut","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1161–Male":"1161–Kuollut","1183–1215":"1183–1215","1120–1161":"1120–1161","about 1161":"noin 1161","1215":"1215","between 1164-1174":"vuodesta 1164 vuoteen 1174","1263":"1263","1120":"1120","before 1161":"ennen vuotta 1161","1140":"1140","before 1140":"ennen vuotta 1140","1183":"1183","1161":"1161","Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Newbigging, Lanarkshire, Scotland","Carnwath, Lanarkshi